  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 1.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "I go the way",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [lit., I am walking (same word as in ver. 3) in the way] ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "of all the earth",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", of all the sons of earth, all mankind (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 17:46",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 10:24",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 66:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc.) The path to Sheol, the path which all his forefathers, and untold millions more, have trod, he is treading it now. The words sound like a ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "reminiscence",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 23, 24",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Perhaps, too, the thought of Joshua suggested to his mind the next words]: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "but",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "be thou strong, and be a man.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [Similar, though not identical, words were four times addressed to Joshua (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 1:6, 7, 9, 18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and David may well have thought that his son, in entering upon his difficult duties, was not at all unlike Joshua when he succeeded Moses in the leadership of Israel, and that he needed similar encouragement. It is not necessary to  suppose, as Canon Rawlinson does (\"Speaker's Com.,\" vol. 2 p. 489), that in the words, \"show thyself a man,\" we have a reference to Solomon's ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "youth",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; for words precisely similar were addressed to each other by the Philistines at Aphek (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 4:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The age of Solomon at his accession is very doubtful. David said, \"Solomon my son is young and tender\" (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 22:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 29:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); and Solomon says of himself, \"I am a little child\" ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "נַעַר קָטֹן",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 3:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Josephus, probably reflecting the tradition of his time, fixes his age at fourteen; Eupolemus at twelve. I incline to think that the words \"young and tender\" almost forbid the favourite opinion that he was about twenty.] 1 Kings 2:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "David's Last Instructions and Death. - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 2:1-4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". When David saw that his life was drawing to a close, he first of all admonished his son Solomon to be valiant in the observance of the commandments of God. \"I go the way of all the world\" (as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 23:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), i.e., the way of death; \"be strong and be a man,\" - not \"bear my departure bravely,\" as Thenius supposes, but prove thyself brave (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 4:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") to keep the commandments of the Lord. Just as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 4:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the object in which the bravery is to show itself is appended simply by the copula Vv; so is it here also with וגו ושׁמרתּ. The phrase יי את־משׁמרת שׁמר, to keep the keeping of Jehovah, which so frequently occurs in the Thorah, i.e., to observe or obey whatever is to be observed in relation to Jehovah (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 26:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 8:35",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 18:30",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc.), always receives its more precise definition from the context, and is used here, as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 26:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", to denote obedience to the law of God in all its extent, or, according to the first definition, to walk in the ways of Jehovah. This is afterwards more fully expanded in the expression וגו חקּתין לשׁמר, to keep the ordinances, commandments, rights, and testimonies of Jehovah. These four words were applied to the different precepts of the law, the first three of which are connected together in ",
        "children": []
      },
